{{other uses}}
A '''mathematical theory''' is a subfield of mathematics that is an area of mathematical research. A theory can be a [[body of knowledge]], and so in this sense a "mathematical theory" refers to an area of mathematical research.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.esotericka.org/cmc/tth.html | title=Theorems and Theories | first=Sam | last=Nelson | website=www.esotericka.org | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819090102/http://www.esotericka.org/cmc/tth.html | archivedate=2014-08-19 | df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| first=Mark C. | last=Chu-Carroll | date=March 13, 2007 | url=http://scienceblogs.com/goodmath/2007/03/13/theories-theorems-lemmas-and-c-1/Theories | title=Theorems, Lemmas, and Corollaries | work=Good Math, Bad Math blog }}</ref>  This is distinct from the idea of [[mathematical model]]s. Branches of mathematics like [[group theory]] and [[number theory]] are examples of this.

